human_system_low,transformer hum,541812,60Hz_Tube_Radio_Hum.wav,"60hz, buzz, click, electric, electricity, hum, humming, noise, radio, tube","Non-functional tube radio warming up, making a loud 60hz hum with lots of harmonics. As a bonus it clicks off at the end. Zenith Consoltone.
Only because the FAQ says so: Electro Voice N/D 257A through impedance transformer into crappy Gigabyte motherboard Realtek High Definition Audio. 16bits, processed at 32bits. Audacity sound editor and/or driver wouldn't record mic level so it was very noisy after amplification. Filtered with a (mathematically equivalent) FFT constructed whopping 64k length zero phase filter (Blackman window) with 5 wavelength width bandpass at each harmonic from 60Hz to 5,520Hz. For some reason a fraction of some of the harmonics didn't get through so did another pass on the residual noise and mixed that in. Near the beginning there was a sort of brief duplicate signal that descended in pitch so it didn't make it through the filter. I added that bit in. Attenuated frequencies above 3.6kHz because they are pretty much noise, but removing them didn't sound right. Cleaned up the beginning a bit in various ways, cut it down to 15 sec and carefully appended the unfiltered ""click"" onto the end, which I denoised 12dB with Audacity's noise reduction.",http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/,wav,15.4463,hetanoyokozuki,681,4.6,2020-11-01T10:26:34Z,1362522,0,16,44100.0,1,https://cdn.freesound.org/previews/541/541812_6378364-hq.mp3,https://cdn.freesound.org/previews/541/541812_6378364-lq.mp3,https://cdn.freesound.org/displays/541/541812_6378364_spec_M.jpg,https://cdn.freesound.org/displays/541/541812_6378364_wave_M.png,https://freesound.org/people/hetanoyokozuki/sounds/541812/,70,92.0,,429.904,11.673,0.357,0.414,20.47,10.709,,True
